        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_6_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm currently applying for a Lecturer in Criminology post at a UK University and one of the application questions regards knowledge of current issues in Criminology and Criminal Justice education.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_6_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've taught Criminology and Criminal Justice modules as part of much broader Social Science or Professional Training degree's for almost 10 years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_6_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is, however, just a small part of my teaching portfolio, meaning current trends and issues relating to teaching in the field is not something I feel I'm on top of.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_6_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You might think this is a good indicator that I'm probably not suitable for the job and you're possibly right; however current personal circumstances mean the job is in a location I'm looking to move to and feel like it's worth an application at least given my experience.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_6_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What would more experienced colleagues suggest are current, pertinent issues relating to teaching and learning in this field?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_7_0</DOCNO>
