        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Significant Cultural Artefacts of Northern Ireland</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I work for a small University Centre in England and, as a team, we are currently developing a resource for students that encourages them to engage and reflect on the impact of 'Cultural Capital' in a bid to widen their knowledge and increase critical thinking skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a fella from Bangor, I'm really keen that Northern Irish culture is represented in this exercise.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was brought up a working class unionist (never identified as Loyalist) and whilst Northern Irish has always been my go to label, I'm far more comfortable with my Irishness than Britishness these days.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With that in mind, I also want to increase students awareness of Britain's relationship with Ireland.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So one of the Cultural Artefacts I've put forward is Bloody Sunday.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My students are wonderful but (and this is found amongst the English public generally too) the ignorance about this part of the world is unreal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other local examples I'm sitting on include The GFA, Freed from Desire at Euro 2016, The Twelfth and St. Patrick's Day but I'd love some more ideas on songs, films, events, etc that are important to this part of the world and - ideally - cross the political divide.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wider examples I've got that might help you out include Band Aid, Music Festivals, Death of Diana, The Millenium (Millenium Bug), Cool Britannia, Labour Government of '45-'51, 9/11, Rage Against The Machine Xmas No.1 of 2009, Remembrance Sunday, Football and Brexit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm desperate to include Maniac 2000 and Bits and Pieces but God knows how to explain them to an English audience!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_16_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Honestly, any ideas or even critiques of mine would be most appreciated.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_17_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Perfect mate, cheers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_17_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Has made me think of 'In the name of the father' too.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_17_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As you can tell from my examples, I'm very Historical minded so this is exactly what I'm looking for.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_18_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I could upvote twice</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2095_19_0</DOCNO>
